Abstraction
Abstraction means dealing with the essential aspects of an object by hiding the implementation details. In other words, abstraction is a process where things are represented (by others) in a way that ignores some of their characteristics (such as their internal structure or implementation detail). It provides a way to reduce complexity and enhance understandability.

In programming, abstraction means hiding the internal details of an object (or class) and only exposing its interface to the outside world. This allows programmers to work with objects without worrying about their implementation details. To achieve abstraction, we can use various techniques, including interfaces, abstract classes, and inheritance.

Here's an example of abstraction in Java:

```java
class Shape {
    abstract double area();
    abstract double perimeter();
}

class Rectangle implements Shape {
    int length;
    int width;
    @Override
    double area() {
        return length * width;
    }
    @Override
    double perimeter() {
        return 2 * (length + width);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Rectangle rectangle = new Rectangle(5, 2);
        System.out.println("Area: " + rectangle.area());
        System.out.println("Perimeter: " + rectangle.perimeter());
    }
}
```

Here, the abstract class Shape defines two abstract methods area and perimeter. The Rectangle class implements the abstract methods of Shape.

