Inheritance allows a class to inherit the properties and behavior of another class. The class inheriting the properties and behavior is called the derived class, and the class whose properties and behavior are inherited is called the base class or parent class. The derived class can have additional properties and behavior, which are not present in the base class.

Inheritance is a way to model the hierarchy in a program. It enables polymorphism, which allows the program to treat objects of different classes through a common interface. It saves time and enables code reusability.

In programming, inheritance enables a class to inherit the implementation of another class. The derived class can use the implementation of the base class, without having to write the code again. This way, inheritance promotes code reuse and makes the program simpler and more structured.

