In this example, Vehicle is the base class (parent class), and Car is the derived (child) class. The Car class inherits the implementation of the run method from the Vehicle class. The Car class can also define additional methods, such as drive.

Inheritance can be either single or multiple. In single inheritance, a class inherits the properties and behavior of one base class. In multiple inheritance, a class inherits the properties and behavior of more than one base class.

Inheritance supports abstraction, polymorphism, and code reuse. When designing a system that uses inheritance, it's essential to plan the hierarchy carefully and define clear relationships between the classes. Always consider the best practices for implementing inheritance in your code.

