A:

To complete the answers provided previously by rpoyer, it has been determined that there is no change in the performance of your CPU with your experiments.
Furthermore, it is likely that your results are a result of different cache behaviors observed in the two scenarios. The sort method called in the optimized version needs more cache space because it needs to store more information (the indices) than the unsorted one.
Your CPU likely has a larger cache and can keep the information faster, reducing the number of cache misses and therefore the need to read or write from memory several times.
The unsorted version has a limited data to process.
You may be using the same CPU and comparing with a simple loop (not a function call), but the function makes your code run in a less optimized way compared to a simple loop which does not need to perform stack pushing and function call stack cleaning.

